# Providing Defaults

An `init()` method is just a special function that runs EXACTLY ONCE when the object is created. Think of it like taking a new car off the assembly line and putting its tires on.

```swift
class Dog {
    var name: String

    init(dogName: String) {
        name = dogName
    }
}
```
Here, the `init(dogName: String)` method takes the input and officially assigns it to the Class's `name` property.

# Fixing Name Clashes

Often, your parameter `name` inside `init` is the exact same word as your Class property `name`.

```swift
class Cat {
    var name: String

    init(name: String) {
        self.name = name // self targets the Class property!
    }
}
```
The keyword `self` explicitly points to the Class instance itself, solving the confusing "Who is who?" problem!
